name: x-adp-z'
desc:
Adapters are short non-functional parts, available in both X-Z' and Z-X' formats, that can be added during a build to switch the end type from X' to Z'  or vice versa. They can be used as band-aids to fix unanticipated design problems on “the fly”, such as linking an X-Z' part to another X-Z' part (or a Z-X' part to another Z-X' part), or, adapting the circuit to whichever anchors and caps remain in your fridge when parts start running out (see below). Alternatively, they can also replace functional parts in circuits as negative controls.

Version RDP 2.0
Plate: E2

name: x-OAr-z'
desc:
Operators (O) provide the flexibility to confer new or enhanced regulatory possibilities for CDS expression. They can be combined with either constitutive or regulatable promoters. Operators are provided in both the X-Z' or Z-X' formats and can therefore be placed to either or both sides of a promoter. 

OAr s the binding site for the AraC repressor (encoded by c.OAr .Rpr). Regulating CDS's with OAr needs an expressible form of  c.OAr .Rpr that has been included some where else in the circuit design. CDS's under OAr regulation are repressed in the absence of the inducer L-arabinose (Ara) and induced by its presence.

name: x-Pr.1-z'
desc:
Constitutive promoters initiate RNA continuously at a rate that cannot be controlled by the experimenter unless they are placed immediately adjacent to an operator(s) on either or both sides (see below). By making limited changes to their DNA sequences, it is possible to create different constitutive promoters whose activity varies over a broad range from weak (Pr.1) to very strong (Pr.4). Constitutive promoters come in both the X-Z' or Z-X' formats to accommodate different promoter/operator combinations. All promoters will always occupy positions that are one or two positions to the left of an Rbs.

name: x-c.Ar.Rpr-z'
desc:
c.Ar.Rpr  encodes the AraC repressor which binds to its operator AraO (OAr). The repressor is released from the operator through its interaction with its inducer, L-arabinose (Ara- provided). 

In E. coli, the AraC repressor and its operator regulate the uptake and utilization of the sugar L-arabinose. As the inducer of AraC, the presence of  L-arabinose activates the expression of the arabinose operon which produces three enzymes that convert arabinose to the metabolizable sugar, D-xylulose-phosphate.

name: x-c.C1.Rpr-z'
desc:
c.C1.Rpr  encodes the λC1 repressor which binds to its operator C1O (OC1). Unlike the Tet, Lac and Ara repressors, λC1 does not have an inducer, therefore regulating any CDS using λC1/ OC1 must incorporate a strategy for turning λC1 on and off  using one of the inducible repressor/operator pairs described above.
In E. coli,  λC1 controls the dormant and active states of bacteriophage λ , (an E. coli virus). Upon infection of the cell, the bacteriophage normally replicates many copies of itself that are released, destroying its host in the process. Occasionally however, the viral chromosome will integrate into the host cell's chromosome as a “prophage” that confers immunity to further infection. As long as the C1 repressor is expressed, the prophage remains dormant. The repression of C1, however, by the λCro repressor initiates a series of events that releases the prophage from the host chromosome resulting in active virus production.

Version RDP 2.0
Plate: D3

name: x-c.InsA-z'
desc:
c.InsA and B  encode the human Insulin A and B chains which form of a two-domain protein that regulates the intake of glucose into mammalian cells. Under oxidative conditions, disulphide bonds link the chains covalently. Each chain is appended at its N-terminus with a 17-amino acid polypeptide tag that contains 8 consecutive histidine residues, and the cleavage site for the factor Xa protease (MHHHHHHHHGSGIEGRG). The histidine stretch facilitates the affinity purification of each chain using a nickel-bound column. Cleavage with factor Xa removes the tag and releases each chain in pure form. Following purification, the chains are mixed under oxidizing conditions and allowed to fold into their native conformation.

Version RDP 2.0

name: x-c.Lc.Rpr-z'
desc:
c.Lc.Rpr  encodes the  repressor LacI which binds to its operator LacO (OLc). When bound to its inducer molecule isopropyl thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG- provided) LacI undergoes a conformational change that releases it from the operator.
In E. coli, LacI and its operator regulate the uptake and utilization of the sugar lactose as a carbon source for energy production and growth. Lactose is the natural inducer of LacI whose presence activates the expression of the lactose operon. The lactose operon produces both a protein that that transports lactose into the cell, and an enzyme that converts lactose glucose and galactose, sugars that can be used by the cell. IPTG is an analogue of lactose that functions as an inducer but unlike lactose, cannot be degraded.

When expressed together, these enzymes convert a fatty acid precursor to luciferin, a chemical compound that emits a greenish glow in the dark. Lux C,D,E,G first convert the precursor to a compound called tetradecanal. LuxA and B encodes subunits of the enzyme luciferase that converts tetradecanal to luciferin.

name: x-c.Tt.Rpr-z'
desc:
c.Tt.Rpr encodes the  TetR repressor which binds to its operator TetO (OTt). TetR also interacts specifically with the inducer, anhydrotetracyclin (ATC- provided). When present, ATC induces a conformational change in TetR, releasing it from the operator.
In Nature, TetR and TetO regulate the resistance of bacteria to the antibiotic tetracylin. The presence of tetracyclin (a natural inducer of TetR) results in the expression of the TetA protein that exports the antibiotic from the cell.  As a modified form of tetracyclin, ATC functions as an inducer but lacks antibiotic activity.

Version RDP 2.0
Plate: A3

name: x-c.VioA-z'
desc:
The Violacein pathway is derived from the soil bacterium Chromobacterium violaceum. It is composed of five enzymes (VioA,B,C,D and E) that work step-wise to convert the amino acid tryptophan, to violacein, a deep purple compound with purported anti-cancer and antimicrobial properties. By using different combinations of the parts, bacterial colonies or cultures can be made to turn violet (VioA,B,E,D,C), royal blue (VioA,B,E,C), or greenish-black  (VioA,B,E,D)

The flavoenzyme VioA and the heme protein VioB work in conjunction to oxidize and dimerize l-tryptophan to a nascent product that can default to the off pathway metabolite chromopyrrolic acid. In the presence of VioE, the intermediate instead undergoes on-pathway [1,2] indole rearrangement to prodeoxyviolacein. The last two enzymes in the pathway are flavin-dependent oxygenases, VioC and VioD, that act sequentially. VioD hydroxylates one indole ring at the 5-position to yield proviolacein, and VioC then acts on the other indole ring at the 2-position to create the oxindole and complete violacein formation. 
(http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17176066)

Version RDP 2.0
Plate: H3
